# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rbac-access-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] In computer security, an **access-control list** (**ACL**) is a list of permissions associated with a system resource (object or facility).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] An ACL specifies which users or system processes are granted access to resources, as well as what operations are allowed on given resources.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Each entry in a typical ACL specifies a subject and an operation.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Many kinds of operating systems implement ACLs or have a historical implementation; the first implementation of ACLs was in the filesystem of Multics in 1965.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] A filesystem ACL is a data structure (usually a table) containing entries that specify individual user or group rights to specific system objects such as programs, processes, or files.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] These entries are known as access-control entries (ACEs) in the Microsoft Windows NT, OpenVMS, and Unix-like operating systems such as Linux, macOS, and Solaris.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Each accessible object contains an identifier to its ACL.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] The privileges or permissions determine specific access rights, such as whether a user can read from, write to, or execute an object.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] In some implementations, an ACE can control whether or not a user, or group of users, may alter the ACL on an object.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] One of the first operating systems to provide filesystem ACLs was Multics.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] PRIMOS featured ACLs at least as early as 1984.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] In the 1990s the ACL and role-based access control (RBAC) models were extensively tested and used to administer file permissions.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] POSIX 1003.1e/1003.2c working group made an effort to standardize ACLs, resulting in what is now known as "POSIX.1e ACL" or simply "POSIX ACL".
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] The POSIX.1e/POSIX.2c drafts were withdrawn in 1997 due to participants losing interest for funding the project and turning to more powerful alternatives such as NFSv4 ACLs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] As of December 2019, no live sources of the draft could be found on the Internet, but it can still be found in the Internet Archive.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Most of the Unix and Unix-like operating systems (e.g.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Linux since 2.5.46 or November 2002, FreeBSD, or Solaris) support POSIX.1e ACLs (not necessarily draft 17).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] ACLs are usually stored in the extended attributes of a file on these systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are much more powerful than POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Unlike draft POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are defined by a published standard, as part of the Network File System.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are supported by many Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Examples include AIX, FreeBSD, Mac OS X beginning with version 10.4 ("Tiger"), or Solaris with ZFS filesystem, support NFSv4 ACLs, which are part of the NFSv4 standard.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] There are two experimental implementations of NFSv4 ACLs for Linux: NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext3 filesystem and the more recent Richacls, which brings NFSv4 ACLs support for Ext4 filesystem.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] As with POSIX ACLs, NFSv4 ACLs are usually stored as extended attributes on Unix-like systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] NFSv4 ACLs are organized nearly identically to the Windows NT ACLs used in NTFS.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] NFSv4.1 ACLs are a superset of both NT ACLs and POSIX draft ACLs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Samba supports saving the NT ACLs of SMB-shared files in many ways, one of which is as NFSv4-encoded ACLs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Microsoft's Active Directory service implements an LDAP server that stores and disseminates configuration information about users and computers in a domain.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Active Directory extends the LDAP specification by adding the same type of access-control list mechanism as Windows NT uses for the NTFS filesystem.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Windows 2000 then extended the syntax for access-control entries such that they could not only grant or deny access to entire LDAP objects, but also to individual attributes within these objects.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] On some types of proprietary computer hardware (in particular, routers and switches), an access-control list provides rules that are applied to port numbers or IP addresses that are available on a host or other layer 3, each with a list of hosts and/or networks permitted to use the service.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Although it is additionally possible to configure access-control lists based on network domain names, this is a questionable idea because individual TCP, UDP, and ICMP headers do not contain domain names.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Consequently, the device enforcing the access-control list must separately resolve names to numeric addresses.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] This presents an additional attack surface for an attacker who is seeking to compromise security of the system which the access-control list is protecting.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Both individual servers and routers can have network ACLs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Access-control lists can generally be configured to control both inbound and outbound traffic, and in this context they are similar to firewalls.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Like firewalls, ACLs could be subject to security regulations and standards such as PCI DSS.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] ACL algorithms have been ported to SQL and to relational database systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Many "modern" (2000s and 2010s) SQL-based systems, like enterprise resource planning and content management systems, have used ACL models in their administration modules.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] In 2024, schema-indexed ACL models emerged as a lightweight alternative to traditional JSON-based permission storage.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] One notable proposal introduced the idea of storing only the indexes of allowed operations, rather than full permission trees.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] This technique, later formalized as *SCode ACL*, allows compact encoding of access rights (e.g., `"0 2 5"`) based on a predefined flattened schema, making it particularly efficient for use in stateless systems such as JWT tokens or session cookies.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] The approach gained early traction in developer communities for its minimalism and performance, and has since been adopted in both small-scale and production-grade systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] The main alternative to the ACL model is the role-based access-control (RBAC) model.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] A "minimal RBAC model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] In modern SQL implementations, ACLs also manage groups and inheritance in a hierarchy of groups.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] So "modern ACLs" can express all that RBAC express and are notably powerful (compared to "old ACLs") in their ability to express access-control policy in terms of the way in which administrators view organizations.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control-list] For data interchange, and for "high-level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:rbac-access-control/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
