[src:rbac-access-control/identity-and-access-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:rbac-access-control/identity-and-access-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:rbac-access-control/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] In computing, **privilege** is defined as the delegation of authority to perform security-relevant functions on a computer system.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] A privilege allows a user to perform an action with security consequences.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Examples of various privileges include the ability to create a new user, install software, or change kernel functions.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Users who have been delegated extra levels of control are called privileged.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Users who lack most privileges are defined as unprivileged, regular, or normal users.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Privileges can either be automatic, granted, or applied for.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] An automatic privilege exists when there is no requirement to have permission to perform an action.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] For example, on systems where people are required to log into a system to use it, logging out will not require a privilege.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Systems that do not implement file protection - such as MS-DOS - essentially give unlimited privilege to perform any action on a file.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] A granted privilege exists as a result of presenting some credential to the privilege granting authority.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] This is usually accomplished by logging on to a system with a username and password, and if the username and password supplied are correct, the user is granted additional privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] A privilege is applied for by either an executed program issuing a request for advanced privileges, or by running some program to apply for the additional privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] An example of a user applying for additional privileges is provided by the `sudo` command to run a command as superuser (*root*) user, or by the Kerberos authentication system.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Modern processor architectures have multiple CPU modes that allows the OS to run at different privilege levels.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Some processors have two levels (such as *user* and *supervisor*); i386+ processors have four levels (#0 with the most, #3 with the least privileges).
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Tasks are tagged with a privilege level.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Resources (segments, pages, ports, etc.) and the privileged instructions are tagged with a demanded privilege level.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] When a task tries to use a resource, or execute a privileged instruction, the processor determines whether it has the permission (if not, a "protection fault" interrupt is generated).
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] This prevents user tasks from damaging the OS or each other.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] In computer programming, exceptions related to privileged instruction violations may be caused when an array has been accessed out of bounds or an invalid pointer has been dereferenced when the invalid memory location referenced is a privileged location, such as one controlling device input/output.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] This is particularly more likely to occur in programming languages such as C, which use pointer arithmetic or do not check array bounds automatically.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Mark Miller has critiqued the framing of privilege as being poorly defined and hard to measure, and suggested that authority can be defined as the set of things a program can do, which is more helpful.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] On Unix-like systems, the superuser (commonly known as 'root') owns all the privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Ordinary users are granted only enough permissions to accomplish their most common tasks.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] UNIX systems have built-in security features.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Most users cannot set up a new user account nor do other administrative procedures.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] The user “root” is a special user, something called super-user, which can do anything at all on the system.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] This high degree power is necessary to fully administer a UNIX system, but it also allows its user to make a mistake and cause system problems.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] On Windows NT-based systems, privileges are delegated in varying degrees.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] These delegations can be defined using the local security policy manager (`secpol.msc`).
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Windows defines a number of administrative privileges that can be assigned individually to users and/or groups.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] An account (user) holds only the privileges granted to it, either directly or indirectly through group memberships.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Upon installation a number of groups and accounts are created and privileges are granted to them.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] However, these grants can be changed at a later time or though a group policy.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Unlike Linux, no privileges are implicitly or permanently granted to a specific account.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Some administrative privileges (e.g. taking ownership of or restoring arbitrary files) are so powerful that if used with malicious intent they could allow the entire system to be compromised.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] With user account control (on by default since Windows Vista) Windows will strip the user token of these privileges at login.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Thus, if a user logs in with an account with broad system privileges, he/she will still not be *running* with these system privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Whenever the user wants to perform administrative actions requiring any of the system privileges he/she will have to do this from an *elevated* process.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] When launching an *elevated* process, the user is made aware that his/her administrative privileges are being asserted through a prompt requiring his/her consent.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Not holding privileges until actually required is in keeping with the principle of least privilege.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Elevated processes will run with the full privileges of the *user*, not the full privileges of the *system*.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Even so, the privileges of the user may still be more than what is required for that particular process, thus not completely least privilege.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] The DOS-based Windows ME, Windows 98, Windows 95 and previous versions of non-NT Windows only operated on the FAT filesystem, did not support filesystem permissions and therefore privileges are effectively defeated on Windows NT-based systems that do not use the NTFS file system.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] The names used in the Windows source code end in either "privilege" or "logonright".
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] This has led to some confusion about what the full set of all these "rights" and "privileges" should be called.
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] Microsoft currently uses the term "user rights".
[src:rbac-access-control/privilege-computing] In the past some other terms have also been used by Microsoft, such as "privilege rights" , "logon user rights" and "nt-rights".
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In information security, **role-based access control** (**RBAC**) or **role-based security** is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] It is a policy-neutral computer access control mechanism defined around roles and privileges.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The components of RBAC, such as role-permissions, user-role and role-role relationships, make it simple to perform user assignments.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC can be used to facilitate administration of security in large organizations with hundreds of users and thousands of permissions.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Although RBAC is different from mandatory access control and discretionary access control (DAC) frameworks, it can enforce these policies.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Its approach is also different from context-based access control and access-control lists.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control and relationship-based access control are models that build on the concept of RBAC.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A 1990s study by NIST demonstrated that RBAC addresses many needs of commercial and government organizations.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC is still commonly considered a best practice in information security management, including in implementation of information security standards related to access control.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Within an organization, roles are created for various job functions.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The permissions to perform certain operations are assigned to specific roles.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Role authorization: A subject's active role must be authorized for the subject.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With rule 1 above, this rule ensures that users can take on only roles for which they are authorized.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Permission authorization: A subject can exercise a permission only if the permission is authorized for the subject's active role.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With rules 1 and 2, this rule ensures that users can exercise only permissions for which they are authorized.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Additional constraints may be applied as well, and roles can be combined in a hierarchy where higher-level roles subsume permissions owned by sub-roles.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] With the concepts of role hierarchy and constraints, one can control RBAC to create or simulate lattice-based access control (LBAC).
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Thus RBAC can be considered to be a superset of LBAC.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A constraint places a restrictive rule on the potential inheritance of permissions from opposing roles.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Thus it can be used to achieve appropriate separation of duties.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For example, the same person should not be allowed to both create a login account and to authorize the account creation.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A subject may have *multiple* simultaneous sessions with/in different roles.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC is a flexible access control technology whose flexibility allows it to implement or discretionary access control (DAC) or mandatory access control (MAC).
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] DAC with groups (e.g., as implemented in POSIX file systems) can emulate RBAC.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] MAC can simulate RBAC if the role graph is restricted to a tree rather than a partially ordered set.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Prior to the development of RBAC, the Bell-LaPadula (BLP) model was synonymous with MAC, and file system permissions were synonymous with DAC.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] These were considered to be the only known models for access control: if a model was not BLP, it was considered to be a DAC model, and vice versa.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Research in the late 1990s demonstrated that RBAC falls in neither category.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Unlike context-based access control (CBAC), RBAC does not look at the message context (such as a connection's source).
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC has also been criticized for leading to role explosion, a problem in large enterprise systems which require access control of finer granularity than what RBAC can provide as roles are inherently assigned to operations and data types.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In resemblance to CBAC, an Entity-Relationship Based Access Control system is able to secure instances of data by considering their association to the executing subject.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Access control lists (ACLs) are used in traditional discretionary access-control (DAC) systems to affect low-level data-objects.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC differs from ACL in assigning permissions to operations which change the direct-relations between several entities (see: *ACLg* below).
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For example, an ACL could be used for granting or denying write access to a particular system file, but it wouldn't dictate how that file could be changed.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In an RBAC-based system, an operation might be to 'create a credit account' transaction in a financial application or to 'populate a blood sugar level test' record in a medical application.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A Role is thus a sequence of operations within a larger activity.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] RBAC has been shown to be particularly well suited to separation of duties (SoD) requirements, which ensure that two or more people must be involved in authorizing critical operations.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Necessary and sufficient conditions for safety of SoD in RBAC have been analyzed.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] An underlying principle of SoD is that no individual should be able to effect a breach of security through dual privilege.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] By extension, no person may hold a role that exercises audit, control or review authority over another, concurrently held role.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] For data interchange, and for "high level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control (ABAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC to consider additional attributes in addition to roles and groups.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] ABAC is policy-based in the sense that it uses policies rather than static permissions to define what is allowed or what is not allowed.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In ReBAC, a subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The advantage of this model is that allows for fine-grained permissions; for example, in a social network where users can share posts with other specific users.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The use of RBAC to manage user privileges (computer permissions) within a single system or application is widely accepted as a best practice.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A 2010 report prepared for NIST by the Research Triangle Institute analyzed the economic value of RBAC for enterprises and estimated benefits per employee from reduced employee downtime, more efficient provisioning, and more efficient access control policy administration.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] In an organization with a heterogeneous IT infrastructure and requirements that span dozens or hundreds of systems and applications, using RBAC to manage sufficient roles and assign adequate role memberships becomes extremely complex without hierarchical creation of roles and privilege assignments.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Newer systems extend the older NIST RBAC model to address the limitations of RBAC for enterprise-wide deployments.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] The NIST model was adopted as a standard by INCITS as ANSI/INCITS 359-2004.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] A discussion of some of the design choices for the NIST model has also been published.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] NIST Special Publication 800-53, an information security standard used by U.S. federal agencies and other organizations, includes role-based access control in its Access Enforcement controls under AC-3(7).
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Implementations of the CIS Controls, a set of best practices, often incorporate role-based access control as part of fulfilling Control 6, Access Control Management.
[src:rbac-access-control/role-based-access-control] Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) regulations require implementation of access control as part of technical safeguards for electronic protected health information (45 CFR 164.312), and role-based access control is a typical approach in the industry.
